Can the euro be fixed?
PARIS – German Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble recently put the option of Greece exiting the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict discipline required by the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a broad discussion about the principles that form the basis of the euro, its governance model, and the rationale for its existence.
Two weeks before Schulz's proposal was put forward, European leaders had already noted the Commission president Juncker's report on the future of the euro, co-authored with colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debates about Greece led many policymakers to believe that it was necessary to return to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens are questioning why they should share a single currency.
Is this meaningful? Can there be a consensus on Greece's future?
Money is like a country; its establishment requires mythology.
Traditionally, it was seen as the political price Germany paid to France for reunification in euros.
In fact, German reunification was just the final step in an engineering project that had been shaping up since the 1980s to address a long-standing dilemma.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, believing them to be incompatible with a single market; yet they were unwilling to maintain a monetary framework dominated by the German central bank in the long term.
A genuine European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In hindsight, Germany’s reunification has been more of a curse than a blessing.
When exchange rates were pegged in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was in difficulty, while France was undervalued and its economy was booming.
In the decade that followed, imbalances began to emerge between the re-emerging Germany and countries that saw credit booms fueled by low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the global financial crisis in 2008, these conditions became fertile ground for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
