Will there be more or less government reform?
It is impossible to establish a baseline for reverse engineering analysis to assess the impact of the euro.
But this is no reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the eurozone economy has performed disappointingly, and its political institutions must take responsibility for this.
What really matters is whether a common European currency remains important for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginably high (and would likely be even higher if the breakup of the eurozone were to occur during a crisis and exacerbate recriminations among the participating countries).
Furthermore, abolishing the euro could unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O'Rourke of the University of Oxford recently pointed out that this view is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should keep their marriage alive simply because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, is the euro still meaningful?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
It is assumed that monetary unions can promote economic integration and strengthen Europe's long-term growth.
Conversely, intra-zone trade and investment growth in the eurozone have been lackluster, while growth potential has actually diminished.
This is partly because the national governments did not take things further towards monetary unification and turned the eurozone into an economic superpower, instead attempting to retain their remaining powers.
This may make sense from a political logic standpoint, but it makes no economic sense: Europe’s huge internal market is one of its main assets, so opportunities to reinforce it must not be squandered.
Secondly, people hope that the euro will become one of the major international currencies (especially given that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and institutional frameworks).
And according to the latest ECB data, this hope has been basically realized.
The euro’s international usage ranks second only to the dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an inconsequential entity.
Third, people (with a touch of naivety) believe that the institutions underpinning the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policies, as if the level of policy-making at the European level is inherently superior to that at the national level.
After the global financial crisis of 2008, a严峻的考验 came: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, resulting in worse performance compared to the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, it must be accompanied by further policy and institutional reforms.
But establishing and implementing a schedule requires a broad consensus on the nature of the problems.
The ongoing debate over the Greek issue illustrates that Europe is far from reaching agreement: participating countries have contradictory analyses of the roots of the debt crisis, leading to contradictory prescriptions.
Richard Cooper, of Harvard University, once observed that during the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases was hindered by the fact that different countries had varying patterns of contagion.
Countries prefer joint actions but cannot formulate a unified plan because they differ on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem that the eurozone faces today.
Fortunately, this problem is not unsolvable, and significant reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism (ESM) and the launch of the banking union have proven this point.
The lack of consistency has not prevented the ECB from taking decisive action, which underscores the importance of institutional governance.
But the fact that reforms and actions have only begun recently, under the pressure of a severe crisis, underscores the difficulty of achieving consensus.
Europe can no longer afford delays and pretenses.
Eurozone members must come up with a coherent schedule for governance and political reform to turn the monetary union into a engine of prosperity, or they will sink into recurrent debates and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is the prerequisite for serious discussions and ambitious reforms.
Now, all major parties have a duty to be clear about what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to offer in exchange for what they want.
